\Sect{2}{Work These Problems}{\SectType{TextMultiPara}}{

\pcap{2}{a}{Problem A}
The rest mass of a \m{\pi^+} (\Quote{pi-plus}) meson is about
140\,MeV/\m{c^2}.
If a \m{\pi^+} is traveling at 0.8\,\m{c}, compute its energy in MeV and momentum
in MeV/\m{c}.

\pcap{2}{b}{Problem B}
In the decay of a \m{\Lambda^0} (\Quote{lambda-zero})
particle, at rest, to a neutron (n) and a \m{\pi^0} (\Quote{pi-zero}), use
conservation of energy and momentum to show that the momentum of the neutron is
104\,MeV/\m{c}.
%
\begin{center}\begin{tabular}{l c l}
mass of \m{ \Lambda^0 } & = & 1115.63\,MeV/\m{c^2} \\
mass of \m{        n  } & = & 939.5656\,MeV/\m{c^2} \\
mass of \m{    \pi^0  } & = & 134.9739\,MeV/\m{c^2} \\
\end{tabular}\end{center}
%
\begin{itemize}
\item [Note:] (momentum)\m{^2 = k^2 v^2 m_0^2 = (k^2 - 1) m_0^2 c^2} is a useful
identity that you can easily prove.

\item [Note:] For further decay problems see, \Quote{Review of Particle
Properties,} {\it Physics Letters}, Vol.\,239, April 12, 1990.
\end{itemize}

You might also like to try Problem 12.28, AF.

